    "instruction": "Load metric.csv, trace.csv, log.csv, and error_logs.csv into memory. For each file, compute and return a compact summary only: 1) total row count; 2) min(timestamp) and max(timestamp); 3) list of unique cmdb_id values (limit to top 20); 4) list of unique KPI/trace/log names (for metric: kpi_name; for trace: trace_name; for log: log_name) limited to top 20; 5) show up to the first 5 rows of the file as sample. Store the full loaded DataFrames in kernel variables for later steps but do not print them. Return results as a small JSON-like dictionary for each file." }

{
    "analysis": "From the initial file summaries we know metric, trace, and log data cover the incident window (metric: 01:00–01:30, trace: 01:00–01:29, log: 01:00–01:30). error_logs.csv is empty. Next we should perform preprocessing and anomaly detection on metrics first (fastest narrowing): calculate global thresholds per component-KPI using the full metric series (not just the incident window), then filter metric points to the incident time range and count anomalies. We will look for both high-side breaches (value >= P95) and low-side breaches (value <= P05) because some KPIs indicate problems when they drop (e.g., traffic, success rate). The goal of this step is a compact ranked list of the most anomalous component-KPIs during the incident window to focus subsequent trace/log analysis.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using the full metric.csv stored in kernel variable df_metric, perform the following and store intermediate tables in memory: 1) For each (cmdb_id, kpi_name) pair, compute global P95 and P05 of the 'value' using all available rows for that pair in df_metric. 2) Filter df_metric to the incident window timestamps from 2021-03-04 01:00:00+08 to 2021-03-04 01:30:00+08 (use timestamps 1614790800 to 1614792600). 3) For each (cmdb_id, kpi_name) within the filtered window, count: total points in window, number of high anomalies where value >= P95, earliest timestamp of such high anomaly (if any), number of low anomalies where value <= P05, earliest timestamp of such low anomaly (if any). 4) Return a compact table with top 20 (cmdb_id, kpi_name) rows sorted by (high_anomaly_count + low_anomaly_count) desc. For each row return: cmdb_id, kpi_name, global_p95, global_p05, total_points_window, high_anomaly_count, earliest_high_anomaly_timestamp, low_anomaly_count, earliest_low_anomaly_timestamp. Also return the total number of distinct (cmdb_id, kpi_name) pairs in metric.csv. Limit returned rows to at most 20." }

{
    "analysis": "We computed global P95/P05 per (cmdb_id,kpi_name) using the full metric series and then counted anomalies in the incident window. The top results are dominated by KPIs where global_p95 == global_p05 (constant metrics such as HeapMemoryMax, some process counters, or zero-valued network counters). Those constant KPIs cause every sample in the window to be flagged both high and low (misleading), so they must be excluded. To make progress we should restrict analysis to the allowed root-cause components and exclude trivial/constant KPIs (global_p95 == global_p05). Then focus on pairs that have non-zero anomaly counts and meaningful deviations.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "From the intermediate tables in memory (df_global, df_window, df_result_top20), produce a compact candidate list limited to the allowed root-cause components: [\"apache01\",\"apache02\",\"Tomcat01\",\"Tomcat02\",\"Tomcat03\",\"Tomcat04\",\"MG01\",\"MG02\",\"IG01\",\"IG02\",\"Mysql01\",\"Mysql02\",\"Redis01\",\"Redis02\"]. Filter df_result_top20 (or recompute using df_global/df_window if needed) to: 1) only include cmdb_id in the allowed list; 2) exclude rows where global_p95 == global_p05 (constant KPI); 3) include only rows with combined_anomaly_count > 0. Return up to 20 rows sorted by combined_anomaly_count desc. For each row return: cmdb_id, kpi_name, global_p95, global_p05, total_points_window, high_anomaly_count, earliest_high_anomaly_timestamp, low_anomaly_count, earliest_low_anomaly_timestamp, combined_anomaly_count. Also return the total number of candidate pairs after filtering. Limit output to these aggregates (do not print full time series)." }

{
    "analysis": "We aggregated metric anomalies and found many candidate components after excluding constant KPIs. Component-level severity ranks Mysql01 and Mysql02 highest (max_pair_severity=19) with earliest significant anomaly timestamps at 2021-03-04T01:00:00+08:00. Several Tomcat, IG/MG, Redis, and Apache nodes also show notable faults. Because multiple high-severity, potentially service-level and node-level components are present, we cannot yet pick a single root-cause component from metrics alone. According to the diagnosis rules, when multiple service- or container-level candidates exist we must use traces to identify the most downstream faulty component in call chains and confirm impact timing. Therefore the next step is a compact trace-level anomaly scan (global thresholds then incident-window filtering) focused on the allowed components to see which services show trace degradation (increased durations or reduced row_count) and their earliest anomaly times.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using trace.csv (kernel variable df_trace): 1) For each (cmdb_id, trace_name) compute global P95 and P05 of 'value' using all available rows for that pair. 2) Filter df_trace to the incident window 2021-03-04 01:00:00+08 to 2021-03-04 01:30:00+08 (timestamps 1614790800 to 1614792600). 3) For each (cmdb_id, trace_name) in the window count: total points, high_anomaly_count (value >= global_p95) and earliest_high_anomaly_timestamp, low_anomaly_count (value <= global_p05) and earliest_low_anomaly_timestamp. 4) Restrict results to allowed components [\"apache01\",\"apache02\",\"Tomcat01\",\"Tomcat02\",\"Tomcat03\",\"Tomcat04\",\"MG01\",\"MG02\",\"IG01\",\"IG02\",\"Mysql01\",\"Mysql02\",\"Redis01\",\"Redis02\"] and to pairs with combined_anomaly_count>0. 5) Return a compact table (limit 20 rows) sorted by combined_anomaly_count desc showing: cmdb_id, trace_name, global_p95, global_p05, total_points_window, high_anomaly_count, earliest_high_anomaly_timestamp, low_anomaly_count, earliest_low_anomaly_timestamp, combined_anomaly_count; also return the total number of distinct (cmdb_id, trace_name) pairs examined. Store intermediate DataFrames in memory for follow-up." }

{
    "analysis": "Trace analysis found many anomalous trace metrics across IG, MG, Tomcat, and docker components. Top trace candidates include edges like MG01.trace.from_dockerA1.row_count, MG02.trace.from_Tomcat03.row_count, IG01.trace.to_Tomcat01.row_count, Tomcat01.trace.from_IG01.row_count, IG02.trace.to_Tomcat01.row_count and Tomcat01.trace.from_IG02.row_count. Many of these are row_count anomalies (indicating traffic drops) or duration_p95 increases. Earliest anomaly timestamps reported in the top results are around 01:00–01:04 for several edges, with some later spikes. Since multiple services show anomalies, we must identify the most-downstream faulty service in the call chains. The next step is to inspect trace candidates specifically involving Tomcat services (both to_TomcatXX and from_TomcatXX) and related MG/IG edges, ordered by the earliest anomaly timestamp, so we can determine which downstream service exhibited the first significant fault.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "From the trace candidates stored in memory (df_trace_candidates or recompute from df_trace_global/df_trace_window if needed), extract rows whose trace_name contains any of: 'to_Tomcat', 'from_Tomcat', 'to_MG', 'from_MG', 'to_IG', 'from_IG'. Restrict to allowed components list. For each matching row compute earliest_anomaly_timestamp = the earlier of earliest_high_anomaly_timestamp and earliest_low_anomaly_timestamp (use whichever exists). For each row return these columns (limit 50 rows): cmdb_id, trace_name, parsed_direction ('to' or 'from'), parsed_target (e.g., 'Tomcat01' when present), combined_anomaly_count, earliest_high_anomaly_timestamp, earliest_low_anomaly_timestamp, earliest_anomaly_timestamp. Sort the output by earliest_anomaly_timestamp ascending, then by combined_anomaly_count desc. Return at most 50 rows." }

{
    "analysis": "We have narrowed candidates using metrics and traces. Metric aggregation flagged many components; component-level severity ranks Mysql01 and Mysql02 highest (max_pair_severity=19) with earliest significant anomalies at 2021-03-04T01:00:00+08. Trace analysis showed widespread row_count and latency anomalies across IG, MG, and Tomcat edges, with many traces reporting anomalies starting at 01:00 (e.g., trace.to_TomcatXX and trace.from_TomcatXX). According to the diagnosis rules, when multiple service-level components are faulty we should pick the most-downstream faulty service in the call chain using traces and confirm the resource reason using logs. Logs are only available for Tomcat and Apache nodes in our dataset, while DB (Mysql) and Redis show strong metric severity but may lack log coverage. Therefore the next logical step is log analysis focused on Tomcat and Apache: check whether Tomcat/apache logs show internal errors (log.error_count) or JVM GC pauses (log.gc_pause_max) anomalies during the incident window. If Tomcat logs show no internal errors or GC issues at or before 01:00, that supports a downstream dependency failure (e.g., Mysql) being the root cause. If Tomcat logs show early internal errors/GC issues at 01:00, Tomcat could be the root cause.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using the in-memory df_log (or load log.csv if needed): 1) Compute global P95 and P05 per (cmdb_id, log_name) using all available rows for that pair. 2) Filter log rows to the incident window timestamps 1614790800 to 1614792600 (2021-03-04 01:00:00+08 to 01:30:00+08). 3) For each (cmdb_id, log_name) where cmdb_id is in [\"Tomcat01\",\"Tomcat02\",\"Tomcat03\",\"Tomcat04\",\"apache01\",\"apache02\"]: report total_points_window, global_p95, global_p05, high_anomaly_count (value >= global_p95) and earliest_high_anomaly_timestamp, low_anomaly_count (value <= global_p05) and earliest_low_anomaly_timestamp, combined_anomaly_count. 4) Additionally, return up to 20 raw rows from the filtered window where log_name == 'log.error_count' and value > 0 (to show any actual error occurrences). Return results as a compact table sorted by combined_anomaly_count desc and include the total number of distinct (cmdb_id, log_name) pairs examined." }

{
    "analysis": "We have followed preprocess -> metric anomaly detection -> trace analysis -> log analysis. Metrics flagged many components; component-level severity ranked Mysql01 and Mysql02 highest (max_pair_severity=19) with earliest significant anomalies at 2021-03-04T01:00:00+08. Traces show widespread row_count and latency anomalies across IG, MG, and Tomcat edges with many earliest anomalies at 01:00, but traces did not clearly show a downstream Tomcat internal fault (Tomcat logs show no non-zero error_count). Logs show some GC and row_count deviations on Tomcat/apache but no clear internal errors at 01:00. Given the high metric severity on Mysql01/02 and Redis01/02 and the lack of Tomcat internal error evidence, the database or Redis nodes are strong root-cause candidates. To decide between them and to identify the exact occurrence time and reason, we need to inspect which specific KPIs on Mysql/Redis drove the high severities (e.g., memory, CPU, network, disk, or Redis-specific metrics like connected_clients or mem_fragmentation_ratio) and the earliest timestamps of those KPI breaches.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using the metric intermediate tables in memory (or recompute from df_metric): For components Mysql01, Mysql02, Redis01, Redis02 produce a compact table of their top faulty KPIs during the incident window. For each (cmdb_id, kpi_name) where combined_anomaly_count>0 (using previously computed global P95/P05 and the 01:00–01:30 window), return: cmdb_id, kpi_name, global_p95, global_p05, total_points_window, max_value (in window), min_value (in window), high_anomaly_count, earliest_high_anomaly_timestamp, low_anomaly_count, earliest_low_anomaly_timestamp, pair_severity (as previously defined). Sort rows by pair_severity desc then combined_anomaly_count desc and limit to top 20 rows. Also return the earliest anomaly timestamp among these rows. Keep outputs compact (only the requested columns)." }

{
    "analysis": "We inspected metrics, traces, and logs. Metric severity ranking shows Mysql01 and Mysql02 have the largest relative deviations (pair_severity = 19) with earliest significant anomalies around 2021-03-04T01:01:00+08. Redis01 shows a later but large CPU WIO deviation (~01:14). Traces show row_count/latency anomalies starting at 01:00 across IG/MG/Tomcat edges, while Tomcat/apache logs show no non-zero error_count at 01:00 (only GC/row_count deviations later). Per the diagnosis rules, the most significant deviation (>>50%) determines the failure level: MySQL node-level metrics exhibit the largest deviations, and Tomcat shows degraded traces without internal errors, consistent with a downstream DB degradation. However, to localize the exact root-cause occurrence time and confirm the spike pattern, we should validate that the MySQL KPI spikes are sudden at the earliest anomaly timestamps (value jump at that minute vs previous minute). I'll therefore request the earliest anomalous sample and its immediate previous sample for the top MySQL KPIs to confirm occurrence time and abruptness.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using metric intermediate tables (df_global and df_window) or recompute if needed, for these specific (cmdb_id,kpi_name) pairs: \n- Mysql01: [\"Mysql-MySQL_3306_Com Insert\",\"Mysql-MySQL_3306_Innodb pages created\",\"Mysql-MySQL_3306_SlowQueries\",\"Mysql-MySQL_3306_Innodb log write requests\",\"Mysql-MySQL_3306_Innodb os log written\"]\n- Mysql02: [\"Mysql-MySQL_3306_Innodb buffer pool pages misc\",\"Mysql-MySQL_3306_max trx lock memory bytes\"]\nFor each pair, within the incident window (timestamps 1614790800 to 1614792600) return a compact table with one row per pair showing: cmdb_id, kpi_name, global_p95, global_p05, earliest_anomaly_timestamp (the earliest of earliest_high_anomaly_timestamp/earliest_low_anomaly_timestamp), value_at_earliest (value at that timestamp), previous_timestamp (one minute earlier row if present), previous_value (value at previous_timestamp or null). Limit output to these rows only (at most 7). This will confirm the exact root-cause occurrence time and whether the KPI had a sudden spike." }

{
    "analysis": "We have followed the required workflow: computed global thresholds, detected anomalies in metrics, narrowed candidates, used traces to understand call edges, and inspected logs. Metric severity and timing point strongly to MySQL nodes as the most significant deviation (pair_severity = 19). Multiple Mysql01 KPIs (Com Insert, Innodb pages created, Innodb log write requests, os log written) show clear high spikes with earliest anomaly timestamps at 2021-03-04T01:01:00+08. Traces show downstream row_count/latency drops at ~01:00 affecting Tomcat/IG/MG interactions, while Tomcat logs do not show internal error spikes at 01:00. Disk I/O KPIs on MySQL hosts also deviate. Taken together and following the rule that the root-cause level is the fault showing the most significant deviation, the evidence points to a MySQL node degradation that began at ~2021-03-04T01:01:00+08. However, both Mysql01 and Mysql02 show issues; Mysql01 exhibits multiple concurrent high-severity write/innodb spikes at 01:01, making it the leading single-component candidate. Before finalizing, we should verify the raw per-minute values around 01:00–01:05 for the top Mysql01 KPIs to confirm the suddenness and exact occurrence minute of the spike (i.e., verify a jump at 01:01 vs earlier minutes).",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "For Mysql01 only, retrieve metric rows for these KPIs: [\"Mysql-MySQL_3306_Com Insert\",\"Mysql-MySQL_3306_Innodb pages created\",\"Mysql-MySQL_3306_SlowQueries\",\"Mysql-MySQL_3306_Innodb log write requests\",\"Mysql-MySQL_3306_Innodb os log written\"]. Filter to timestamps from 2021-03-04 01:00:00+08 (1614790800) through 2021-03-04 01:05:00+08 (1614791100) inclusive. For each KPI return up to 10 rows with columns: timestamp, dt, cmdb_id, kpi_name, value. Sort rows by kpi_name then timestamp ascending. This will confirm the exact minute when each KPI jumped (or dropped) and allow final determination of the root-cause occurrence time and abruptness." }

